<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Verdana, Arial" COLOR="#00ff00">Originally posted by Schlegnir on 07-17-2001 11:34 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">I'm opposed to 'cheating' when it makes it harder for other people to enjoy the game to any significant degree.  I never used speed-hacks or any other -hacks.  I have however used SEQ, for a couple of simple reasons:

1) It's a more convenient navigation tool than /loc and a printed map.

2) I don't have to bug the druids / rangers in the zone so much when I'm trying to get something rare to spawn.

If I had to stop using SEQ I would definitely leave the game.  Point number 2 I could live with, but not point 1.  If EQ had some kind of in-game map I wouldn't need SEQ.  I mean, come on, even some text-based muds have maps!

The major problem I see with EQ is that they are making downtime the primary investment that you as a player are putting into your character!

I realized the other day when I saw some monk with a RotLC, this isn't a particulary brave or mighty monk - it's a monk that:

1) Sat around in S Karana for days shouting '100pp to whoever spots Qwinn'.

2) Sat around in L Guk for over 100 hours waiting for Raster to spawn.

3) Sat around in Sol B for 20 hours waiting the the Rock guy to spawn.

Most of the cheats / hacks are just ways people are trying to reduce downtime.  This is really a game problem, not a player problem!  Some people find other solutions to this problem;

1) Read books in your downtime.

2) Get two computers and switch back and forth, so you play one character while the other one is medding/healing and vice versa.

-M

[This message has been edited by Schlegnir (edited 07-17-2001).]</TEXTAREA>
